Medical Cost Differences Between Patient Clusters in the U.S.

Xiran Wang

I. Advanced Inference for Linear Regression

This work uses the MEPS dataset to address the question of whether men and women use roughly the same quantity of medical services at each age. That is, to determine whether the age-dependence of average transformed medical expenditures (\(log_{10}(cost+100)\) ) is roughly the same for men and for women. Be aware that when perform log10 transfermation on depedndent variable(medical cost), log10 transfermation is not able to work on 0 medical cost because \(log_{10}(0)\) mathematically doesn’t exist. Therefore, 100 dollars are added on each medical cost to make it aslo work on 0 medical cost, that is \(log_{10}(cost+100)\)

II. Dataset Availability

The dataset is provided by the Medical Expenditure Panel Survey (MEPS), and the code book is available at https://meps.ahrq.gov/mepsweb/data_stats/download_data_files_codebook.jsp?PUFId=H129&sortBy=Start.

4.1 Age effect

To further explore the linear relationship observed in the figure above, I used a linear regression model with spline transformation to describe the effect of age on medical expenditure. Firstly, age 39 is identified as a knot in this case. Then, based on the following linear regresion fit, from ages 0-39, the medical expenditure does not seem to have significant changes for different age cluster. However, after age 39, the medical expenditure increases exponentially as age increases.

mars <- earth(h129.TOTEXP09 ~ h129.AGE09X, data = newdata)

4.4 Model diagnostics

Based on residual plot for the model,the residuals are not normally distributed, and equal variance doesn’t hold for these errors. The Q-Q plot and boxplot also show the evidences that the residuals have fewer possiblities to be linearlity, and the residuals might be skewed. In addition, I needed to check both influential points and outliers: a few observations should not dominate the model fit.

4.5 Log10 trasformation on dependent variable

The model estimated in the MLR model(fitlinear) is likely to substantially be influenced by one or a few extreme observations. A better alternative is to model lexp=log10(expenditure + 100). Fitting a MLR of log10 expenditure on age (possibly with splines), gender, interaction between age (possibly with splines), gender, and interaction between age (possibly with splines) and gender.

Here , I test the null hypothesis that the dependence of mean \(Log_{10}(expenditure)\) of age is the same for men and women. The output shows the results of the partial F-test. Since F=352.28 (p-value< 2.2e-16).We reject the null hypothesis (\(\beta_2 = \beta_3 = \beta_4 =0\)) at the 5% level of significance. It appears that the variables “gender”,“genderage“,and”genderI(age>29) contribute the significant information to mean(Lexpend), which also suggests that there are interation between gender and age, as well as between gender and I(age>29), once the variables age and I(age>29) have been taken into consideration. Overall,the dependence of mean(Lexpend) on age is not the same for men and women.

V. Results

5.1 Defination of the final MLR model

\[ \begin{eqnarray} E[log_{10}(expenditure)] = 2.5646 + 0.0091*age &+& 0.0061I(age>29)^+ + 0.2065\times gender(male)\\ &-&0.0214\times age\times gender(male) + 0.0302I(age>29)^+\times gender(male) \end{eqnarray} \]

5.2 Estimation of log10(expenditure) for each cluster

log10(expenditure) of Male < 29 years old: \(\beta_0+ \beta_1+ \beta_3+ \beta_4\)

log10(expenditure) of Female < 29 years old: \(\beta_0+ \beta_1\)

log10(expenditure) of Male > 29 years old: \(\beta_0+ \beta_1+\beta_2+\beta_3+ \beta_4+\beta_5\)

log10(expenditure) of Female > 29 years old: \(\beta_0+ \beta_1+\beta_2\)

the intercept: \(\beta_0\) = 2.5646

5.3 Coefficient interpretation

\(\beta_2\)=0.0091: hold all other variables unchange, the difference of expected log10(expenditure) between fmales who => 29 years old and <29 years old is 0.0091 dollors.

\(\beta_5\) = 0.0061: hold all other variables unchange, the difference of expected log10(expenditure) between the difference of males who <29 years old and =>29 years old and the difference females who <29 years old and =>29 years old is 0.0061 dollors.

\(\beta_3+\beta_4\) = 0.1851: hold all other variables unchange, the difference of expected log10(expenditure) for male and female who <29 years old is 0.1047668 dollars.

\(\beta_3+\beta_4+\beta_5\) = 0.2154: hold all other variables unchange, the difference of expected log10(expenditure) for male and female who >=29 years old is 0.2154 dollars.

5.4 Difference of log10(expenditure) between gender Next, use the esticon function in R to calculate the estimated difference between female and male in averag of log10(exp.) and its standard error at age 40,age 65, and age 80. See the table below.

library(doBy)
refitmlr <- lm(lexp ~ h129.AGE09X + re.agesp1 + factor(gender) + h129.AGE09X*factor(gender)
             + re.agesp1*factor(gender), data = renewdata)

estimate <- function(age){
  lamda <- c(0,0,0,-1,-age,-(age-29))
  e <- esticon(refitmlr,lamda)
  mytable <- data.frame(e$estimate,e$std.error,e$lwr,e$upr)
  
return(mytable)
}

5.5 Inference of medical expenditure and its’ standard error - boostrap and delta method approach

There is a significant difference of medical expenditure between male and female under the same age, based on my regression model, for female who is under 29 years old, the median of the medical expenditure increases by 1.023269 \((=10^{0.0100} )\) dollars for every unit(year) increase in age. For femaleas who are older than 29 years old, the increase rate of medical expenditure increase an additional \(1.0123(=10^{0.0053})\) dollars for every unit(yeart) increase on the female’s age after 29 years old.

For male who under 29 years old, the median of the medical expenditure increases by 0.9722\((=10^{0.0099898-0.0222252})\) dollars for every unit(year) increases on ages. For female who is order than 29 years old, the increase rate of medical expenditure increases, and an additional 1.0874 \((=10^{0.0053111+0.0310784} )\) dollars when the male becomes one year older than 29 years old.

The estimated difference(female-male) of male and female’s medical expenditure shows that, in gengeral, an individual female has more expenses on medicalsthan a individual male, before middle age, however, these differences are geting smaller when people get older. Finally, at age 60, an individual male has more expenses on medical services than a individual female. Such as, at age 40, the meidan medical expenditure difference between female and male is 511.7077 dollars, based on the 95% confidence interval, the true difference of median medical cost between female and male has 95% probability to be secured between 472.3110 dollars and 551.1044 dollars. Likely, at age 60, the true meidan medical expenditure difference between female and male is -385.9292 dollars, according to the 95% confidence interval, the true difference median has 95% possibility to be located somewhere between 423.9967 dollars and 502.7901 dollars.

########### Delta Method ############
library(msm)

ages <- c(40,65,80)
d1 <- deltamethod(~10^(x1+40*x2+(40-29)*x3)-
                    10^(x1+40*x2+(40-29)*x3+x4+40*x5+(40-29)*x6),
            coef(refitmlr), vcov(refitmlr))


d2 <- deltamethod(~10^(x1+65*x2+(65-29)*x3)-
              10^(x1+65*x2+(65-29)*x3+x4+65*x5+(65-29)*x6),
            coef(refitmlr), vcov(refitmlr))

d3 <- deltamethod(~10^(x1+80*x2+(80-29)*x3)-
              10^(x1+80*x2+(80-29)*x3+x4+80*x5+(80-29)*x6),
            coef(refitmlr), vcov(refitmlr))


############## Bootstrap ############

# nboots = 100  #1000 , 10000
Boots <- function(exps,age,gender,wantedage, nboots=100){
  
  diffmeanest <- matrix(NA,nrow=nboots)
  rawdat      <- data.frame(exps,age,gender)
  rawdata1    <- rawdat[!is.na(rawdat[,1]) & !is.na(rawdat[,2])& !is.na(rawdat[,3]), ]
  for (i in 1:nboots) {
    idexsamp <- sample(1:nrow(rawdata1),nrow(rawdata1),replace = T)
    datasam  <- rawdata1[idexsamp,] # get rows of the data
    age29    <- ifelse(datasam[,2]>29, datasam[,2]-29, 0)
    bootsfit <- lm(datasam[,1]~datasam[,2]+ age29+ gender+ datasam[,2]*gender+
                   age29*gender)
    
    diffmean <- 10^( coef(bootsfit)[1] + coef(bootsfit)[2]*wantedage + coef(bootsfit)[3]*(wantedage-29) )-
               (10^(coef(bootsfit)[1]+ coef(bootsfit)[2]*wantedage+ coef(bootsfit)[3]*(wantedage-29) +
                coef(bootsfit)[4]+ coef(bootsfit)[5]*(wantedage)+ coef(bootsfit)[6]*(wantedage-29)))
    
    diffmeanest[i,] <- diffmean
  }
  
  varout <- apply(diffmeanest,2,var)
  #median<- median(diffmeanest)
  #ci    <- quantile(diffmeanest,c(.25,.975))
  sd.err <- sqrt(varout)
  return(sd.err)
}

b1 <- Boots(renewdata$lexp,renewdata$h129.AGE09X,renewdata$gender,40)
b2 <- Boots(renewdata$lexp,renewdata$h129.AGE09X,renewdata$gender,65)
b3 <- Boots(renewdata$lexp,renewdata$h129.AGE09X,renewdata$gender,80)
# Invert log10expenditure back to normal scale

########### Compute Median ###########

fmage <- function(age){

  lamdaf <- c( 1, age, (age-29), 0, 0, 0)
  f      <- esticon(refitmlr,lamdaf)$estimate
  lamdam <- c( 1, age,(age-29),1,age,(age-29))
  m      <- esticon(refitmlr,lamdam)$estimate
  diff   <- (10^(f)-10^(m))

  return(diff)
}
cis <- cbind(rbind(fmage(40)-b1*1.96,fmage(65)-b1*1.96,fmage(65)-b1*1.96),
      rbind(fmage(40)+b1*1.96,fmage(65)+b1*1.96,fmage(65)+b1*1.96))


median <- rbind(fmage(40),fmage(65),fmage(80))
deltamethod <- rbind(d1,d2,d3)
table12 <- data.frame(median,deltamethod,rbind(b1,b2,b3),cis)


colnames(table12) <- c('Estimated Diff In Median expend','Std Error(Delta Method)',
                     'Std Error(bootstrap)',  ' 95%CI lower ',' 95%CI upper' )
row.names(table12) <- c('40','65','80')
kable(table12) %>%
  kable_styling(bootstrap_options = "striped", full_width = F)
